                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-221-off1240 t18301028-221-victim1856"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>GEORGE KEARSLEY DAVISON. I am a <rs id="t18301028-221-viclabel1242" type="occupation">printing-ink-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-221-victim1856 t18301028-221-viclabel1242"></join>. I was passing in Holborn on the 15th of October, about eleven o'clock, near <placeName id="t18301028-221-crimeloc1243">Chancery-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-221-crimeloc1243" type="placeName" value="Chancery-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-221-crimeloc1243" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-221-off1240 t18301028-221-crimeloc1243"></join>, walking with my father, who is very lame; he was leaning on my arm- I felt my handkerchief taken from my pocket; I turned and saw the prisoner and another - I collared them; the other got away - the prisoner got from me; I caught him by the tail of his coat, and the tail of his coat came off - he crossed the way, and some gentleman caught him; this handkerchief was taken from behind his back- it is mine.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you see it taken from him? A. Yes; I do not think it possible for another person to have put it up his back.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. There were three lads following the gentleman; I got before them and some person called Stop thief! - the gentleman seized another lad, but he got away; knowing I was innocent I went to clear myself, and tried to get the other - I never had the handkerchief.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 20.</p>
               <p>
